<br>
Bane, this was so very true!  Traveller was one of the few RPGs in the ancient days that officially endorsed the idea of character permanent death.  If you die, you die.  No magic, no resurrections.  Even all the high technologies of the Third Imperium (roughly circa 2,900 AD) could not bring dead people back to life.  <br>
<br>
Then again, rolling up a character and &quot;skilling up&quot; in Traveller was far far easier and less time consuming than typical D&amp;D or fantasy based games.   Traveller was not an experience level  based game.  It was purely a skill based game.  You pre-selected your preferred skills and template career at the start.  Then you eventually trained more and developed mastery over time.  Some skills could be unlearned in order to learn others, or even make a career change. <br>
<br>
So a &quot;brand newly rolled character&quot; in Traveller would already begin adventuring as a battle-hardened space marine, or a veteran asteroid miner and prospector, or an already experienced scout ship pilot, or a veteran of the Imperial Diplomatic Corps, etc, or a seasoned thug and space pirate, or even role play as a middle-aged gray haired and retired Commodore of the Solomani Navy. <br>
<br>
The average AGE of a newly rolled character in Traveller was roughly a 35 or 39 year old man or woman.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
It was almost impossible (or discouraged) to roll up a young adult character in Traveller, because young characters had less career terms, and thus they begin adventuring with LESS skills points behind their portfolio.  Hence, the average character on Traveller was a middle aged man or woman who possessed tons of skill points to back them up.  It was so completely different from D&amp;D character generation. <br>
<br>
