<br>
As to Call of Cthulu, a guy in my area used to run a Call of Cthulu game religiously. Whenever we would play he would start the session by telling us about real 1920's lore that was printed in his book to help get people more in an eerie mood. Not fantasy lore, REAL lore about real strange occurences which happened. Very eerie. The guy also used to go to places, map them out, and then design adventures around the places. After the adventure was over he would then take his group out to the site where their characters had the adventure in.<br>
<br>
My one friend that had the liberty of going through this, was telling me about this cave complex in a rural setting where they went against some cultists. After the game they were taken out to the actual site and my friend said how unnerving he felt when he saw where his character leaned against this tree to shoot a ghoul by a nearbye cave entrance. And yes, this guy was that good of a DM. He used to really sucker people into the mood. We used to run games at cons together, and for Call of Cthulu, he was the best. What is more eerie about Cthulu, is the facts behind the Lovecraftian stories. Theres more fact to some of what Lovecraft put to pen then most people even realize, very eerie stuff.<br>
<br>
OMG Car Wars rocked! I still have the deluxe set up stairs. My only complaint about that game was they never made more rules for outside of your cars :/ I always thought how cool it would have been to actually play in a more RP fashion with it like how Battletech did when Fasa came out with the Mechwarrior RPG.<br>
<br>
Paranoia rocked! OMG talk about an insane game. I refused to play after one day of losing two clone families all in the same session LOL. As funny as it was, it was also very sucky. Although I did get some good payback as my friend had a clone named &quot;Bubba&quot; and I got to help him crash the computer by crashing his jet into its main data banks ahahaha. Afterwards they built a shrine there and called it &quot;Bubba's Breakaway&quot; LOL.<br>
